Class AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue<K,E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>

        • com.analog.lyric.collect.AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue<K,E>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.Queue<E>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    KeyedPriorityQueue, UniquePriorityQueue

    @NotThreadSafe
@NonNullByDefault(value=false)
public abstract class AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue<K,E>
extends java.util.AbstractQueue<E>
implements java.io.Serializable
    Abstract base class for priority queue with unique keys which can be computed from the elements themselves.

      • offer

        public boolean offer(E element)
        Adds element to the queue if it does not already contain an element with the same key. Unlike add(E) this will return false instead of throwing an exception if the element was not added because its key was found.

        If the element comparator() is null, indicating that natural ordering should be used, then this method will attempt to cast the element to Comparable.

        Specified by:
        offer in interface java.util.Queue<E>
        Throws:
        java.lang.ClassCastException - if queue has no explicit comparator and element is not an instance of Comparable
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if element is null

      • comparator

        @Nullable
public final java.util.Comparator<? super E> comparator()
        The comparator used to determine priority order among elements in the queue. If null, then natural ordering of elements will be used and methods that add elements to the queue will only accept Comparable objects.
